  "local_port": 46052,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why do bolts and nuts not get welded, when both are the same metal and their crystal structure is the same?",
  "response": "Bolts and nuts typically do not get welded together during normal use due to several reasons, even if they are made of the same metal and have similar crystal structures:\n\n1. **Surface Oxidation**: Most metals used in bolts and nuts, such as steel, readily oxidize when exposed to air, forming a thin layer of oxide on their surfaces. This oxide layer acts as a barrier that prevents direct metal-to-metal contact necessary for welding.\n\n2. **Lack of Heat**: Welding requires high temperatures to melt the metal at the joint. The friction between a bolt and nut, even when tightened significantly, does not generate enough heat to reach the melting point of the metal.\n\n3. **Pressure and Time**: Welding processes like friction welding require not only heat but also sustained pressure over a period of time. The pressure applied when tightening a bolt and nut is typically not sufficient, nor is it maintained long enough, to cause welding.\n\n4. **Surface Contaminants**: There may be oils, greases, or other contaminants on the surfaces of the bolt and nut that further inhibit any potential for welding.\n\n5. **Material Differences**: Even if the bolt and nut are made of the same type of metal, slight variations in composition or heat treatment can affect their welding behavior. For instance, one might be harder or more brittle than the other, reducing the likelihood of welding.\n\n6. **Design and Function**: Bolts and nuts are designed to be removable fasteners, not permanent joints. The threads on bolts and nuts are designed to distribute the force over a larger area, reducing the localized pressure and heat that could potentially lead to welding.\n\nIn specific scenarios, such as high-temperature environments or extreme pressure, there is a possibility for bolts and nuts to seize or even weld together, a phenomenon known as galling. However, under normal conditions, the factors listed above prevent welding from occurring.",
